But d5xc4 seems like a clean capture winning a bishop.

- 10...dxc4 (black pawn captures white bishop on c4) so black gains a bishop for a pawn.

Then 11.Qxd8 Rxd8 black recapture with rook. So queens off. So final material: White lost bishop and queen? No white's queen got captured by rook in recapture. So white lost queen? Let's compute properly:

White has rooks at a1 and f1; rooks can't capture pawn on c4.

So dxc4 seems strongly fine. It is a known idea: In the Giuoco Pianissimo sorts black plays ...dxc4 exchanging bishop and then because queen exchange, black emerges with good position.

Now let's check if there are any illegal aspects or pinned piece issues: We must ensure 10...dxc4 doesn't leave black's rook attacked on f8 due to some tactic: After 10...dxc4 11.Qxd8 Rxd8 12.Rad1 be careful.
